 goals        = \n  | longest wins       = \n  | longest unbeaten   = \n  | longest losses     = \n  | highest attendance = \n  | lowest attendance  = \n  | average attendance = \n  | prevseason         = [[2001\u201302 Ukrainian First League|2001\u201302]]\n  | nextseason         = [[2003\u201304 Ukrainian First League|2003\u201304]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2002\u201303 Ukrainian First League''' was the twelfth season of the [[Ukrainian First League]] which was won by [[FC Zirka Kirovohrad|Zirka Kirovohrad]]. The season started on July 6, 2002, and finished on June 21, 2003.\n\n==Promotion and relegation==\n===Promoted teams===\nFive clubs promoted from the [[2001\u201302 Ukrainian Second League]].\n;Group A\n* [[FC Krasyliv]] &ndash; champion ''(debut)''\n* [[FC Sokil Zolochiv|Sokil Zolochiv]] &ndash; runner-up ''(debut)''\n;Group B\n* [[FC Systema-Boreks Borodyanka|Systema-Boreks Borodyanka]] &ndash; champion ''(debut)''\n;Group C\n* [[FC Spartak Sumy|FC Sumy]] &ndash; champion ''(returning after a season)''\n* [[FC Arsenal Kharkiv|Arsenal Kharkiv]] &ndash; runner-up ''(debut)''\n\n=== Relegated teams ===\nOne club was relegated from the [[2001-02 Ukrainian Premier League|2001-02 Ukrainian Top League]]:\n* [[FC Zakarpattia Uzhhorod]] &ndash; 14th place ''(returning after a season)''\n\n===Renamed teams===\n* Before the season [[FC Spartak Sumy|FC Sumy]] changed back to '''[[FC Spartak Sumy]]''' .\n* During winter break SC Mykolaiv changed its name to '''[[MFC Mykolaiv]]'''.\n\n===Teams===\nIn 2002-03 season, the Ukrainian First League consists of the following teams:\n\n{{Location map+|Ukraine|AlternativeMap = Ukraine (1991-2014) location map.svg|width=900|float=none|caption=Locations of teams in '''First League'''|places=\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.000278 |long=37.805278 |label=[[FC Shakhtar-2 Donetsk|Shakhtar-2]]|position=left }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=48.5      |long=32.266667 |label=[[FC Zirka Kirovohrad|Zirka]]|position=left }}\n{{Location map~|Ukraine|lat=