|Olexandria]] has folded in the [[Ukrainian Premier League|Premier League]]. [[FC Spartak Ivano-Frankivsk|Prykarpattya Ivano-Frankivsk]] was bought out by LUKOIL, the main sponsor of [[LUKOR Kalush]], and the new management recognized it as the first team of one club with  [[LUKOR Kalush|LUKOR]] being its second. One a paper [[LUKOR Kalush|LUKOR]] got promoted and [[FC Spartak Ivano-Frankivsk|Prykarpattya Ivano-Frankivsk]] got relegated, but the truth is that the teams stayed in their divisions. [[FC Sokil Zolochiv|Sokil Zolochiv]] has folded.\n|col_P=#D0F0C0|text_P=Promoted to [[Ukrainian Premier League|Top League]]\n|result1=P|result2=P\n|col_NR=inherit|text_NR=Avoided relegation\n|result17=NR\n|col_WNEWP=silver|text_WNEWP=Withdrew\n|result18=WNEWP\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; margin: 0 auto;\"\n|-\n!Persha Liha 2002-03 Winners\n|-\n|[[FC Zirka Kirovohrad]]<br/>Second title\n|}\n\n== Top scorers ==\nStatistics are taken from here.<ref>[http://ukranianfootball.narod.ru/2003/2002_03_p.html Statistics] {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Scorer\n!Goals (pen.)\n!Team\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Maksym Shtayer]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|15 (4)\n|[[FC Krasyliv]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Artem Milevsky]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|11\n|[[FC Dynamo-2 Kyiv|Dynamo-2 Kyiv]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Myroslav Bundash]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|11 (6)\n|[[FC Zakarpattia Uzhhorod|Zakarpattia Uzhhorod]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Bohdan Yesyp]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|10\n|[[FC Naftovyk Okhtyrka|Naftovyk Okhtyrka]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Pavlo Parshyn]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|9 (3)\n|[[FC Polissya Zhytomyr|Polissya Zhytomyr]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Oleksandr Melaschenko]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|8\n|[[FC Dynamo-2 Kyiv|Dynamo-2 Kyiv]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Dmytro Vorobey]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|8 (1)\n|[[FC Dynamo-2 Kyiv|Dynamo-2 Kyiv]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Oleksandr Aliyev]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|8 (1)\n|[[FC Dynamo-2 Kyiv|Dynamo-2 Kyiv]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Ruslan Platon]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|8 (3)\n|[[FC Karpaty-2 Lviv|Karpaty-2 Lviv]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Ruslan Bidnenko]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|7\n|[[FC Borysfen Boryspil|Borysfen Boryspil]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://rsssf.com/tableso/oekr03.html]\n\n{{Ukrainian First League Seasons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2002-03 Ukrainian First League}}\n[[Category:Ukrainian First League seasons]]\n[[Category:2002\u201303 in Ukrainian association football leagues]]\n[[Category:2002\u201303 in European second tier association football leagues|Ukra]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFinal table", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2002%E2%80%9303_Ukrainian_First_League"}
{"title_page": "L'Estaca", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n\n[[File:Llu\u00eds Llach.jpg|thumb|right|165px|[[Llu\u00eds Llach]]]]{{Infobox song|cover=|type=Song|artist=Llu\u00eds Llach|language=Catalan|English_title=The Stake|written=1968|venue=|genre=Nova can\u00e7o|writer=Llu\u00eds Llach}}\n'''L'Estaca''' ({{IPA-ca|l\u0259s\u02c8tak\u0259}}; meaning \"the stake\", figurative sense \"without liberty\") is a song composed by the [[Catalans|Catalan]] artist [[Llu\u00eds Llach]] in 1968.\n\nThe song, which has been translated into several languages,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vilaweb.cat/www/elpunt/noticia?p_idcmp=-735266|title=Una can\u00e7\u00f3 que volta el m\u00f3n|date=2003-12-28|website=www.vilaweb.cat|publisher=VilaWeb - El Punt|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref> has become so popular in some countries that it is erroneously considered to be a locally written song. It was composed during the [[Francoist Spain|reign]] of [[caudillo]] [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] in [[Spain]] and is a call for unity of action to achieve freedom. The song has become a symbol of the fight for freedom everywhere.\n\nPolish singer-songwriter [[Jacek Kaczmarski]] was inspired to write new lyrics to the melody of ''L'Estaca'' after hearing the song on one of several Spanish records he borrowed from a friend in December 1978. The result was ''[[Mury (song)|Mury]]'', which became one of his most famous compositions after it was adopted by the [[Poland|Polish]] [[trade union]] [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarno\u015b\u0107]] and sung at countless rallies, meetings, protests and strikes throughout Poland during the 1980s.\n\nLakadjina and Yasser Jeradi made a version of the song that became the anthem of the Tunisian Revolution in 2011<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.publico.es/internacional/islamistas-presentan-favoritos-comicios-tunecinos.html|title=Los islamistas se presentan como favoritos en los comicios tunecinos|access-date=2017-09-18|language=es-ES}}</ref> \n\n''L'Estaca'' is also an anthem for the supporters of the [[Rugby union|rugby]] team [[USA Perpignan|USAP]], of [[Perpignan]] in [[Northern Catalonia]], in [[France]].\n\nThe song was covered in [[Yiddish]] (under the title \"Der Yokh\") by the American [[klezmer]] band, [[The Klezmatics]], in their 2016 album Apikorism.\n\nThe song was also sung in Bilbao in Basque on September 16, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.cat/ca/politica/manifestacio-bilbao-referendum-catala_192180_102.html|title=Gran manifestaci\u00f3 a Bilbao a favor del refer\u00e8ndum catal\u00e0|website=ElNacional.cat|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref> in support of Catalonia's Referendum on Independence scheduled for October 1, 2017 before a crowd of 32,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.naiz.eus/eu/hemeroteca/gara/editions/2017-09-17/hemeroteca_articles/solidaridad-multitudinaria-con-catalunya-y-en-defensa-propia|title=Solidaridad multitudinaria con Catalunya y en defensa propia|last=SA|first=Baigorri Argitaletxea|date=2017-09-16|work=GARA|access-date=2017-09-18|language=es}}</ref>.\n\n== Lyrics ==\n\nThe lyrics describe the struggle for freedom using a metaphor of being tied to a stake.\n\nThe song is a conversation held in a doorway at dawn, where the main character asks Grandfather Siset \"Don't you see the stake that we're all tied to? If we can't take it down, we'll never be able to walk.\" and the old man tells him that the only way to get free is by working together: \"If we all pull, it will fall down. If I pull this way and you pull that way, it will surely fall, fall, fall, and we will be able to liberate ourselves.\" \n\nThe struggle for freedom is hard, it is never over, there is no rest. \n\nLlach says that when he originally composed the song, he used the word 'column' instead of 'stake'. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aX4eZ1fpYwA Listen to ''L'Estaca'' on YouTube]\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.lluisllach.cat/catala/lestac.htm|title=Lletra: ''L'Estaca'' (lyrics in Catalan)|author=Lluis Llach|date=2002|accessdate=2011-09-15}}\n\n[[Category:Catalan-language songs]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n\n[[File:Llu\u00eds Llach.jpg|thumb|right|165px|[[Llu\u00eds Llach]]]]{{Infobox song|cover=|type=Song|artist=Llu\u00eds Llach|language=Catalan|English_title=The Stake|written=1968|venue=|genre=Nova can\u00e7o|writer=Llu\u00eds Llach}}\n'''L'Estaca''' ({{IPA-ca|l\u0259s\u02c8tak\u0259}}; meaning \"the stake\", figurative sense \"without liberty\") is a song composed by the [[Catalans|Catalan]] artist [[Llu\u00eds Llach]] in 1968.\n\nThe song, which has been translated into several languages,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vilaweb.cat/www/elpunt/noticia?p_idcmp=-735266|title=Una can\u00e7\u00f3 que volta el m\u00f3n|date=2003-12-28|website=www.vilaweb.cat|publisher=VilaWeb - El Punt|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref> has become so popular in some countries that it is erroneously considered to be a locally written song. It was composed during the [[Francoist Spain|reign]] of [[caudillo]] [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] in [[Spain]] and is a call for unity of action to achieve freedom. The song has become a symbol of the fight for freedom everywhere.\n\nPolish singer-songwriter [[Jacek Kaczmarski]] was inspired to write new lyrics to the melody of ''L'Estaca'' after hearing the song on one of several Spanish records he borrowed from a friend in December 1978. The result was ''[[Mury (song)|Mury]]'', which became one of his most famous compositions after it was adopted by the [[Poland|Polish]] [[trade union]] [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarno\u015b\u0107]] and sung at countless rallies, meetings, protests and strikes throughout Poland during the 1980s.\n\nLakadjina and Yasser Jeradi made a version of the song that became the anthem of the Tunisian Revolution in 2011<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.publico.es/internacional/islamistas-presentan-favoritos-comicios-tunecinos.html|title=Los islamistas se presentan como favoritos en los comicios tunecinos|access-date=2017-09-18|language=es-ES}}</ref> \n\n''L'Estaca'' is also an anthem for the supporters of the [[Rugby union|rugby]] team [[USA Perpignan|USAP]], of [[Perpignan]] in [[Northern Catalonia]], in [[France]].\n\nThe song was covered in [[Yiddish]] (under the title \"Der Yokh\") by the American [[klezmer]] band, [[The Klezmatics]], in their 2016 album Apikorism.\n\nThe song was also sung in Bilbao in Basque on September 16, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elnacional.cat/ca/politica/manifestacio-bilbao-referendum-catala_192180_102.html|title=Gran manifestaci\u00f3 a Bilbao a favor del refer\u00e8ndum catal\u00e0|website=ElNacional.cat|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref> in support of Catalonia's Referendum on Independence scheduled for October 1, 2017 before a crowd of 32,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.naiz.eus/eu/hemeroteca/gara/editions/2017-09-17/hemeroteca_articles/solidaridad-multitudinaria-con-catalunya-y-en-defensa-propia|title=Solidaridad multitudinaria con Catalunya y en defensa propia|last=SA|first=Baigorri Argitaletxea|date=2017-09-16|work=GARA|access-date=2017-09-18|language=es}}</ref>.\n\n== Lyrics ==\n\nThe lyrics describe the struggle for freedom using a metaphor of being tied to a stake.\n\nThe song is a conversation held in a doorway at dawn, where the main character asks Grandfather Siset \"Don't you see the stake that we're all tied to? If we can't take it down, we'll never be able to walk.\" and the old man tells him that the only way to get free is by working together: \"If we all pull, it will fall down. If I pull this way and you pull that way, it will surely fall, fall, fall, and we will be able to liberate ourselves.\" \n\nThe struggle for freedom is hard, it is never over, there is no rest. \n\nLlach says that when he original composed the song, he used the word 'column' instead of 'stake'. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aX4eZ1fpYwA Listen to ''L'Estaca'' on YouTube]\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.lluisllach.cat/catala/lestac.htm|title=Lletra: ''L'Estaca'' (lyrics in Catalan)|author=Lluis Llach|date=2002|accessdate=2011-09-15}}\n\n[[Category:Catalan-language songs]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n", "name_user": "Iconodocks", "label": "safe", "comment": "'originally' (adverb) is correct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%27Estaca"}
{"title_page": "Mount Hagen Airport", "text_new": "{{short description|Airport in Mount Hagen, Papua New Guinea}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Mount Hagen Airport\n| nativename   =\n| nativename-a =\n| nativename-r =\n| image        = Mt. Hagen, Kagamuga International Airport 01.JPG\n| image-width  = 250px\n| caption      =\n| IATA         = HGU\n| ICAO         = AYMH\n| pushpin_map            = Papua New Guinea#Oceania\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in [[Mount Hagen]] , [[Papua New Guinea]]\n| pushpin_label          = '''HGU'''/AYMH\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| FAA          =\n| LID          =\n| type         =  Public<ref>{{cite web |title=World Aero Data: MOUNT HAGEN -- AYMH |url=https://worldaerodata.com/wad.cgi?id=PP83878 |website=worldaerodata.com |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n| owner        = \n| operator     =\n| owner-oper   = National Airports Corporation (NAC) of Papua New Guinea\n| city-served  = Mount Hagen\n| location     = Kagamuga, Papua New Guinea\n| elevation-f  = 5386\n| elevation-m  = 1641\n| coordinates  = {{Coord|05|49|36.44|S|144|17|45.10|E|type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| website      =\n| metric-elev  =\n| metric-rwy   =\n| r1-number    = 08/26<ref>{{cite web |title=World Aero Data: MOUNT HAGEN Runway 08/26 |url=https://worldaerodata.com/wad.cgi?runway=PP8387826 |website=worldaerodata.com |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n| r1-length-f  = 3,599\n| r1-length-m  = 1,097\n| r1-surface   = Asphalt\n| r2-number    = 12/30<ref>{{cite web |title=World Aero Data: MOUNT HAGEN Runway 12/30 |url=https://worldaerodata.com/wad.cgi?runway=PP8387830 |website=worldaerodata.com |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n| r2-length-f  = 7,185\n| r2-length-m  = 2,190\n| r2-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    =\n| stat1-header =\n| stat1-data   =\n| stat2-header =\n| stat2-data   =\n| footnotes    = Source: World Aero Data [http://worldaerodata.com/wad.cgi?id=PP83878]\n}}\n\n'''Mount Hagen Airport''' {{airport codes|HGU|AYMH}} is the second biggest airport in [[Papua New Guinea|Papua New Guinea (PNG)]] and is located in the Waghi Valley, 13&nbsp;km north-east of [[Mount Hagen]], the capital of Western Highlands Province of [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref name=\":0\"/> The airport has one terminal and two runways, and is operated by its owner, National Airports Corporation of Papua New Guinea.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe airport underwent a renovation starting in 2013.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.airport-technology.com/projects/mount-hagen-international-airport/|title=Mount Hagen International Airport|website=Airport Technology|language=en-GB|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\nConstructed at a low level, the pre-existing terminal building was exposed to a water drainage problem and regularly got affected by waterlogging.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nThe reconstruction fell into the scope of the Civil Aviation Development Investment Program (CADIP)<ref name=\":0\"/> aimed to increase the safety, accessibility and reliability of the airports in PNG.<ref>{{cite web |title=Civil Aviation Development Investment Program (CADIP) Project Updates |url=https://www.nac.com.pg/cadip/cadip-projects/ |website=www.nac.com.pg |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\nThe Government of PNG and the [[Asian Development Bank|Asian Development Bank (ADB)]] jointly funded the airport development project.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nReconstructed at a cost of approximately [[Papua New Guinean kina|PGK]]&nbsp;70m ([[United States dollar|US$]]23m), the main terminal building reopened in 2015.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adb.org/news/mount-hagen-airport-opens-after-adb-supported-upgrade|title=Mount Hagen Airport Opens After ADB-Supported Upgrade|last=Bank|first=Asian Development|date=2015-11-26|website=Asian Development Bank|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mt. Hagen, Kagamuga International Airport 02.JPG|thumb|200px|left|Terminal building of Kagamuga International Airport in Mt. Hagen]]\nA local artefact, the Mount Hagen axe, provided inspiration for the design of the newly constructed terminal, with the exteriors shaped like the axe and decorated in traditional patterns.<ref name=\":0\"/> The sewerage treatment system integrated into the construction of the building converts the liquid waste into fertiliser after separating it from the solid waste.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nIn 2018, the airport was closed for two days due to security issues arising after a dispute between guards and a local landowning group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.rnz.co.nz/article/071c0cad-4a0d-4d6b-92ca-5f4e65578575|title=Mt Hagen airport to remain closed until security issues are resolved|website=amp.rnz.co.nz|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2018-09-07|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://postcourier.com.pg/kagamuga-flights-resume-today-says-nac-boss/|title=Kagamuga flights to resume today, says NAC boss|last=Taime|first=Mal|website=Post Courier|date=2018-09-07|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019/2020, the Mount Hagen Airport was used to re-route the flights of Air Niugini from Wapenamanda due to maintenance works at the runways performed by the National Airports Corporation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Air Niugini suspends flights to Wapenamanda |url=https://postcourier.com.pg/air-niugini-suspends-flights-to-wapenamanda/ |website=Post Courier |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n{{airport-dest-list\n| [[Air Niugini]] | [[Jacksons International Airport|Port Moresby]], [[Wewak Airport|Wewak]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/272180/air-niugini-adds-mount-hagen-wewak-from-march-2017/|title=Air Niugini adds Mount Hagen \u2013 Wewak from March 2017|publisher=routesonline|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref> \n| Hevilift | [[Jacksons International Airport|Port Moresby]] <br>'''Charter:''' [[Cairns Airport|Cairns]]\n| [[Mission Aviation Fellowship|MAF]] | [[Telefomin Airport|Telefomin]], Sumbai\n| [[PNG Air]] | [[Goroka Airport|Goroka]], [[Kiunga Airport|Kiunga]] [[Moro Airport|Moro]], [[Jacksons International Airport|Port Moresby]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]],<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/51166-png-air-schedules-mount-hagen-intl-debut-for-mid-1q17 | title=PNG Air schedules Mount Hagen int'l debut for mid-1Q17 | work=[[ch-aviation]] | date=28 November 2016 | accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref> [[Tabubil Airport|Tabubil]], [[Wewak Airport|Wewak]]\n| \n}}\n\n[[File:Air Niugini Fokker 100 Mt Hagen PNG.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Air Niugini]] [[Fokker 100|Fokker-100 (P2-ANH)]]  parked at Mt. Hagen's Kagamuga Airport]]\nAir Nuigini operates daily services to Port Moresby with [[Fokker 100|Fokker 100 aircraft]].\nPNG Air operates daily services with [[ATR 72#ATR 72\u2013600|ATR72-600 aircraft]].\n\n==Facilities==\nMt. Hagen International airport has one main terminal housing Air Niugini, Hevilift, and PNG Air. The airport facility has been rebuilt from the ground up, and reopened in November 2015. In 2019, the baggage x-ray machine was supplied by the [[Department of Home Affairs (Australia)|Australian Government, Department of Home Affairs]] free of charge and delivered on a [[Royal Australian Air Force]] [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C130 aircraft]] from Port Moresby to Mount Hagen.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Department of Foreign Affairs |title=Aust supports efficient customs service delivery at Mt Hagen Airport |url=https://png.embassy.gov.au/pmsb/1050.html |website=png.embassy.gov.au |publisher=Australian High Commission Papua New Guinea |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Runways==\nKagamuga Airport features two runways. The main runway bears the designation 12/30 and measures 2'190&nbsp;m in length with 30&nbsp;m in width.<ref name=\":0\"/> The second runway is designated as 08/26 and is 1'097&nbsp;m long and 18&nbsp;m wide.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nNavigational aids equipment of both runways includes [[Precision approach path indicator|precision approach path indicator (PAPI)]], [[Non-directional beacon|non-directional (radio) beacon (NDB)]], [[Distance measuring equipment|distance measuring equipment (DME)]], and [[Air traffic control#Air control or local control|approach and tower (TWR) facilities]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Oceania|Aviation}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Papua New Guinea]]\n[[Category:Western Highlands Province]]\n\n\n{{oceania-airport-stub}}\n{{PapuaNewGuinea-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Airport in Mount Hagen, Papua New Guinea}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Mount Hagen Airport\n| nativename   =\n| nativename-a =\n| nativename-r =\n| image        = Mt. Hagen, Kagamuga International Airport 01.JPG\n| image-width  = 250px\n| caption      =\n| IATA         = HGU\n| ICAO         = AYMH\n| pushpin_map            = Papua New Guinea#Oceania\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in [[Mount Hagen]] , [[Papua New Guinea]]\n| pushpin_label          = '''HGU'''/AYMH\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| FAA          =\n| LID          =\n| type         =\n| owner        = \n| operator     =\n| owner-oper   = National Airports Corporation (NAC) of Papua New Guinea\n| city-served  = Mount Hagen\n| location     = Kagamuga, Papua New Guinea\n| elevation-f  = 5386\n| elevation-m  = 1641\n| coordinates  = {{Coord|05|49|36.44|S|144|17|45.10|E|type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| website      =\n| metric-elev  =\n| metric-rwy   =\n| r1-number    = 08/26\n| r1-length-f  = 3,599\n| r1-length-m  = 1,097\n| r1-surface   = Asphalt\n| r2-number    = 12/30\n| r2-length-f  = 7,185\n| r2-length-m  = 2,190\n| r2-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    =\n| stat1-header =\n| stat1-data   =\n| stat2-header =\n| stat2-data   =\n| footnotes    = Source: World Aero Data [http://worldaerodata.com/wad.cgi?id=PP83878]\n}}\n\n'''Mount Hagen Airport''' {{airport codes|HGU|AYMH}} is the second biggest airport in [[Papua New Guinea|Papua New Guinea (PNG)]] and is located in the Waghi Valley, 13&nbsp;km north-east of [[Mount Hagen]], the capital of Western Highlands Province of [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref name=\":0\"/> The airport has one terminal and two runways, and is operated by its owner, National Airports Corporation of Papua New Guinea.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe airport underwent a renovation starting in 2013.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.airport-technology.com/projects/mount-hagen-international-airport/|title=Mount Hagen International Airport|website=Airport Technology|language=en-GB|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\nConstructed at a low level, the pre-existing terminal building was exposed to a water drainage problem and regularly got affected by waterlogging.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nThe reconstruction fell into the scope of the Civil Aviation Development Investment Program (CADIP)<ref name=\":0\"/> aimed to increase the safety, accessibility and reliability of the airports in PNG.<ref>{{cite web |title=Civil Aviation Development Investment Program (CADIP) Project Updates |url=https://www.nac.com.pg/cadip/cadip-projects/ |website=www.nac.com.pg |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\nThe Government of PNG and the [[Asian Development Bank|Asian Development Bank (ADB)]] jointly funded the airport development project.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nReconstructed at a cost of approximately [[Papua New Guinean kina|PGK]]&nbsp;70m ([[United States dollar|US$]]23m), the main terminal building reopened in 2015.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adb.org/news/mount-hagen-airport-opens-after-adb-supported-upgrade|title=Mount Hagen Airport Opens After ADB-Supported Upgrade|last=Bank|first=Asian Development|date=2015-11-26|website=Asian Development Bank|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mt. Hagen, Kagamuga International Airport 02.JPG|thumb|200px|left|Terminal building of Kagamuga International Airport in Mt. Hagen]]\nA local artefact, the Mount Hagen axe, provided inspiration for the design of the newly constructed terminal, with the exteriors shaped like the axe and decorated in traditional patterns.<ref name=\":0\"/> The sewerage treatment system integrated into the construction of the building converts the liquid waste into fertiliser after separating it from the solid waste.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nIn 2018, the airport was closed for two days due to security issues arising after a dispute between guards and a local landowning group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.rnz.co.nz/article/071c0cad-4a0d-4d6b-92ca-5f4e65578575|title=Mt Hagen airport to remain closed until security issues are resolved|website=amp.rnz.co.nz|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2018-09-07|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://postcourier.com.pg/kagamuga-flights-resume-today-says-nac-boss/|title=Kagamuga flights to resume today, says NAC boss|last=Taime|first=Mal|website=Post Courier|date=2018-09-07|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019/2020, the Mount Hagen Airport was used to re-route the flights of Air Niugini from Wapenamanda due to maintenance works at the runways performed by the National Airports Corporation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Air Niugini suspends flights to Wapenamanda |url=https://postcourier.com.pg/air-niugini-suspends-flights-to-wapenamanda/ |website=Post Courier |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=18 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n{{airport-dest-list\n| [[Air Niugini]] | [[Jacksons International Airport|Port Moresby]], [[Wewak Airport|Wewak]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/272180/air-niugini-adds-mount-hagen-wewak-from-march-2017/|title=Air Niugini adds Mount Hagen \u2013 Wewak from March 2017|publisher=routesonline|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref> \n| Hevilift | [[Jacksons International Airport|Port Moresby]] <br>'''Charter:''' [[Cairns Airport|Cairns]]\n| [[Mission Aviation Fellowship|MAF]] | [[Telefomin Airport|Telefomin]], Sumbai\n| [[PNG Air]] | [[Goroka Airport|Goroka]], [[Kiunga Airport|Kiunga]] [[Moro Airport|Moro]], [[Jacksons International Airport|Port Moresby]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]],<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/51166-png-air-schedules-mount-hagen-intl-debut-for-mid-1q17 | title=PNG Air schedules Mount Hagen int'l debut for mid-1Q17 | work=[[ch-aviation]] | date=28 November 2016 | accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref> [[Tabubil Airport|Tabubil]], [[Wewak Airport|Wewak]]\n| \n}}\n\n[[File:Air Niugini Fokker 100 Mt Hagen PNG.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Air Niugini]] [[Fokker 100|Fokker-100 (P2-ANH)]]  parked at Mt. Hagen's Kagamuga Airport]]\nAir Nuigini operates daily services to Port Moresby with [[Fokker 100|Fokker 100 aircraft]].\nPNG Air operates daily services with [[ATR 72#ATR 72\u2013600|ATR72-600 aircraft]].\n\n==Facilities==\nMt. Hagen International airport has one main terminal housing Air Niugini, Hevilift, and PNG Air. The airport facility has been rebuilt from the ground up, and reopened in November 2015. In 2019, the baggage x-ray machine was supplied by the [[Department of Home Affairs (Australia)|Australian Government, Department of Home Affairs]] free of charge and delivered on a [[Royal Australian Air Force]] [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C130 aircraft]] from Port Moresby to Mount Hagen.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Department of Foreign Affairs |title=Aust supports efficient customs service delivery at Mt Hagen Airport |url=https://png.embassy.gov.au/pmsb/1050.html |website=png.embassy.gov.au |publisher=Australian High Commission Papua New Guinea |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Runways==\nKagamuga Airport features two runways. The main runway bears the designation 12/30 and measures 2'190&nbsp;m in length with 30&nbsp;m in width.<ref name=\":0\"/> The second runway is designated as 08/26 and is 1'097&nbsp;m long and 18&nbsp;m wide.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nNavigational aids equipment of both runways includes [[Precision approach path indicator|precision approach path indicator (PAPI)]], [[Non-directional beacon|non-directional (radio) beacon (NDB)]], [[Distance measuring equipment|distance measuring equipment (DME)]], and [[Air traffic control#Air control or local control|approach and tower (TWR) facilities]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Oceania|Aviation}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Papua New Guinea]]\n[[Category:Western Highlands Province]]\n\n\n{{oceania-airport-stub}}\n{{PapuaNewGuinea-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Limptimon", "label": "safe", "comment": "sources added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Hagen_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Lijomol Jose", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Indian film actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lijomol Jose\n| image              = Lijomol-jose-actress.jpg\n| birth_date         = March \n| residence          =          \n| alma mater         =Pondicherry University\n| death_place        = \n| other_names        = Lijo\n| occupation         = Actress\n| yearsactive        = 2016-Present\n}}\n\n'''Lijomol Jose''', is an Indian film actress, who primarily appears in [[Cinema of Kerala|Malayalam]] films. She made her acting debut in the highly acclaimed Malayalam film ''Maheshinte Prathikaaram'' (2016), following which she went on to act in movies like ''Kattappanayile Rithwik Roshan'' (2016) and ''Honey Bee 2.5'' (2017)<ref>{{cite web|title=Lijomol Jose Biography|url=https://www.filmibeat.com/celebs/lijo-mol-jose/biography.html|publisher=Filmibeat|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref>\n \n== Professional career ==\n\nLijomol started her professional career as a staff reporter for Jaihind TV. Later she quit her job for doing Post Graduation. During this time, she attended an audition for [[Dileesh Pothan]]'s directional debut, Maheshinte Prathikaaram in which she portrayed the role of Soniya, daughter of Babychayan played by [[Alencier Ley Lopez]]. Even though she had a brief role, her combination scenes with [[Soubin Shahir]] were well received in theaters. In her second film, Kattappaniyile Rithwik Roshan, she was given a lengthy role and the film went on to become a huge success.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Language !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2016 || ''[[Maheshinte Prathikaaram]]'' || Soniya || [[Malayalam]] || \n|-\n| ''[[Kattappanayile Rithwik Roshan]]'' || Kani || Malayalam || \n|-\n\n| 2017 || ''[[Honey Bee 2.5]]'' || Kanmani || Malayalam ||\n|-\n\n| rowspan=3| 2018 || ''[[Street Lights]]'' || Remya || Malayalam|| \n|-\n| ''[[Premasoothram]]'' || Ammukutty || Malayalam || \n|-\n| ''Ottakkoru Kaamukan'' || Kathrina || Malayalam ||\n|-\n| rowspan=1| 2019 || ''[[Sivappu Manjal Pachai]]'' ||Raji  || [[Tamil language|Tamil]]||\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n\u25cc Zee Cine Awards 2020( Tamil) Best Debut Actor (Female) for the movie Sivappu Manjal Pachai\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=7934649|name=Lijomol Jose}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jose, Lijomol}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Malayalam television]]\n[[Category:Indian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{India-film-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Indian film actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lijomol Jose\n| image              = Lijomol-jose-actress.jpg\n| birth_date         = March \n| residence          =          \n| alma mater         =Pondicherry University\n| death_place        = \n| other_names        = Lijo\n| occupation         = Actress\n| yearsactive        = 2016-Present\n}}\n\n'''Lijomol Jose''', is an Indian film actress, who primarily appears in [[Cinema of Kerala|Malayalam]] films. She made her acting debut in the highly acclaimed Malayalam film ''Maheshinte Prathikaaram'' (2016), following which she went on to act in movies like ''Kattappanayile Rithwik Roshan'' (2016) and ''Honey Bee 2.5'' (2017)<ref>{{cite web|title=Lijomol Jose Biography|url=https://www.filmibeat.com/celebs/lijo-mol-jose/biography.html|publisher=Filmibeat|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref>\n \n== Professional career ==\n\nLijomol started her professional career as a staff reporter for Jaihind TV. Later she quit her job for doing Post Graduation. During this time, she attended an audition for [[Dileesh Pothan]]'s directional debut, Maheshinte Prathikaaram in which she portrayed the role of Soniya, daughter of Babychayan played by [[Alencier Ley Lopez]]. Even though she had a brief role, her combination scenes with [[Soubin Shahir]] were well received in theaters. In her second film, Kattappaniyile Rithwik Roshan, she was given a lengthy role and the film went on to become a huge success.<ref>{{cite web|title=It's the time of love, not wedding|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/mollywood/301117/its-the-time-of-love-not-wedding.html|publisher=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Language !! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2016 || ''[[Maheshinte Prathikaaram]]'' || Soniya || [[Malayalam]] || \n|-\n| ''[[Kattappanayile Rithwik Roshan]]'' || Kani || Malayalam || \n|-\n\n| 2017 || ''[[Honey Bee 2.5]]'' || Kanmani || Malayalam ||\n|-\n\n| rowspan=3| 2018 || ''[[Street Lights]]'' || Remya || Malayalam|| \n|-\n| ''[[Premasoothram]]'' || Ammukutty || Malayalam || \n|-\n| ''Ottakkoru Kaamukan'' || Kathrina || Malayalam ||\n|-\n| rowspan=1| 2019 || ''[[Sivappu Manjal Pachai]]'' ||Raji  || [[Tamil language|Tamil]]||\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n\u25cc Zee Cine Awards 2020( Tamil) Best Debut Actor (Female) for the movie Sivappu Manjal Pachai\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=7934649|name=Lijomol Jose}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jose, Lijomol}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Malayalam television]]\n[[Category:Indian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\